SIMPLE: stannic
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stannic
<hw>Stan"nic</hw> <pr>(-n⟦icr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>stannum</ets> tin: cf. F. <ets>stannique</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to tin; derived from or
containing tin; specifically, designating those compounds in which the
element has a higher valence as contrasted with <contr>stannous</contr>
compounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stannic acid</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A hypothetical
substance, <chform>Sn(OH)4</chform>, analogous to silicic acid, and
called also <altname>normal stannic acid</altname>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>Metastannic acid.</cd> -- <col><b>Stannic chloride</b></col>, <cd>a
thin, colorless, fuming liquid, <chform>SnCl4</chform>, used as a
mordant in calico printing and dyeing; -- formerly called
<altname>spirit of tin</altname>, or <altname>fuming liquor of
Libavius</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Stannic oxide</b></col>, <cd>tin
oxide, <chform>SnO2</chform>, produced artificially as a white amorphous
powder, and occurring naturally in the mineral cassiterite. It is used
in the manufacture of white enamels, and, under the name of
<altname>putty powder</altname>, for polishing glass, etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stanniferous</ent>⟦br⟧
